Use the public `@qlever-llc/trellis-test` integration harness when a service
repository needs to test against a real Trellis control plane, real auth and
authority behavior, generated client surfaces, NATS/JetStream, resources, jobs,
operations, or live events.

The out-of-tree workflow has two public entrypoints:

- `@qlever-llc/trellis-test/integration` for test helpers such as
  `trellisIntegrationTest`, `runtimeScopeForCase`, and case-scoped naming.
- `@qlever-llc/trellis-test/integration/runner` for a generic Deno runner that
  can run selected cases serially or with one shared runtime for parallel
  workers.

External service repos provide their own Trellis command. The package does not
assume the Trellis monorepo layout.

## Install dependencies

Add the Trellis runtime, Trellis test package, and the schema library your
contracts use to the service repo's Deno config or package manifest. For Deno
repos, that usually means import-map entries like these:

```json
{
  "imports": {
    "@qlever-llc/trellis": "jsr:@qlever-llc/trellis@^0.11.0",
    "@qlever-llc/trellis/service/deno": "jsr:@qlever-llc/trellis@^0.11.0/service/deno",
    "@qlever-llc/trellis-test": "jsr:@qlever-llc/trellis-test@^0.11.0",
    "@qlever-llc/trellis-test/integration": "jsr:@qlever-llc/trellis-test@^0.11.0/integration",
    "@qlever-llc/trellis-test/integration/runner": "jsr:@qlever-llc/trellis-test@^0.11.0/integration/runner",
    "typebox": "npm:typebox@^1.1.33"
  }
}
```

Use the version range that matches the Trellis runtime your service repo targets.

## 1. Add `trellis.integration.ts`

Put the runner config at the service repo root, or another stable path you pass
with `--config`.

```ts
import type { TrellisIntegrationRuntimeOptions } from "@qlever-llc/trellis-test/integration";
import type { TrellisIntegrationRunnerConfig } from "@qlever-llc/trellis-test/integration/runner";

const keepWorkdir = Deno.env.get("TRELLIS_TEST_KEEP_WORKDIR") === "1";

export const integrationRuntime = {
  keepWorkdir,
  trellis: {
    mutableDev: true,
    command: {
      cmd: Deno.execPath(),
      args: ["run", "-A", "./trellis/main.ts"],
      cwd: Deno.cwd(),
    },
  },
  timeouts: {
    startupMs: 60_000,
    reconciliationMs: 15_000,
    waitForMs: 10_000,
    shutdownMs: 10_000,
  },
} satisfies TrellisIntegrationRuntimeOptions;

export default {
  runtime: integrationRuntime,
  denoTestArgs: ["-A", "-c", "deno.json"],
  cases: [
    {
      id: "billing.invoice-created",
      fixture: "billing",
      file: "integration/billing/invoice_created.integration_test.ts",
      testName: "billing.invoice-created calls the invoice RPC",
      coverage: ["rpc", "smoke"],
    },
  ],
} satisfies TrellisIntegrationRunnerConfig;
```

`denoTestArgs` are passed to the child `deno test` process before runner-managed
flags and files. Use them for permissions, `-c`, lockfile options, or import-map
arguments that belong to your service repo.

## 2. Write one case per test module

Parallel Deno workers can execute modules concurrently. Keep one
`trellisIntegrationTest(...)` case per module so the runner can safely map each
case descriptor to one test name and one file.

```ts
import { assertEquals } from "@std/assert";
import {
  defineAppContract,
  defineServiceContract,
  Result,
} from "@qlever-llc/trellis";
import { TrellisService } from "@qlever-llc/trellis/service/deno";
import { Type } from "typebox";
import {
  caseScopedContractId,
  caseScopedName,
  caseScopedSubject,
  integrationSlug,
  runtimeScopeForCase,
  trellisIntegrationTest,
} from "@qlever-llc/trellis-test/integration";
import { integrationRuntime } from "../../trellis.integration.ts";

const CASE_ID = "billing.invoice-created" as const;
const slug = integrationSlug(CASE_ID);

const schemas = {
  CreateInput: Type.Object({ invoiceId: Type.String() }),
  CreateOutput: Type.Object({ invoiceId: Type.String(), status: Type.String() }),
} as const;

const billingServiceContract = defineServiceContract({ schemas }, (ref) => ({
  id: caseScopedContractId("billing.invoice-service", CASE_ID),
  displayName: `Billing Invoice Service (${slug})`,
  description: "Integration-test invoice service.",
  capabilities: {
    createInvoice: {
      displayName: "Create invoices",
      description: "Allows the invoice RPC to be called.",
    },
  },
  rpc: {
    "Invoice.Create": {
      version: "v1",
      subject: caseScopedSubject("rpc.v1.billing", CASE_ID, "Invoice.Create"),
      input: ref.schema("CreateInput"),
      output: ref.schema("CreateOutput"),
      capabilities: { call: ["createInvoice"] },
      errors: [],
    },
  },
}));

const billingClientContract = defineAppContract(() => ({
  id: caseScopedContractId("billing.invoice-client", CASE_ID),
  displayName: `Billing Invoice Client (${slug})`,
  description: "Integration-test invoice client.",
  uses: {
    required: {
      billing: billingServiceContract.use({ rpc: { call: ["Invoice.Create"] } }),
    },
  },
}));

const serviceName = caseScopedName("billing-invoice-service", CASE_ID);
const clientName = caseScopedName("billing-invoice-client", CASE_ID);
const invoiceId = caseScopedName("invoice", CASE_ID);

trellisIntegrationTest({
  name: "billing.invoice-created calls the invoice RPC",
  scope: runtimeScopeForCase(CASE_ID),
  runtime: integrationRuntime,
  async fn(runtime) {
    await runtime.deployments.create({ mutableDev: true });
    await runtime.contracts.approve({
      contract: billingServiceContract,
      allowPlanClassifications: ["update"],
    });

    const serviceKey = await runtime.services.provisionInstanceOnly({});
    const service = await TrellisService.connect({
      trellisUrl: runtime.trellisUrl,
      contract: billingServiceContract,
      name: serviceName,
      sessionKeySeed: serviceKey.seed,
      telemetry: false,
      server: {},
    }).orThrow();

    try {
      await service.handle.rpc.invoice.create(({ input }) =>
        Result.ok({ invoiceId: input.invoiceId, status: "created" })
      );

      const client = await runtime.connectClient({
        name: clientName,
        contract: billingClientContract,
      });

      const created = await client.rpc.invoice.create({ invoiceId }).orThrow();
      assertEquals(created, { invoiceId, status: "created" });
    } finally {
      await service.stop();
    }
  },
});
```

Use `services.provisionInstanceOnly(...)` when the test starts the service
process or `TrellisService.connect(...)` call itself and only needs valid service
session-key material. Use `services.createInstance(...)` when the behavior under
test is the runtime-visible service instance record itself.

## 3. Run serially

Serial runs invoke `deno test` directly. Without a shared runtime manifest, each
test starts its own isolated Trellis runtime from the `runtime` option passed to
`trellisIntegrationTest(...)`. The usual pattern is to export that runtime object
from `trellis.integration.ts` and import it into each test module, as shown above.
The runner config's `runtime` is used directly by the shared runtime host in
parallel mode.

```sh
deno run -A jsr:@qlever-llc/trellis-test/integration/runner \
  --config trellis.integration.ts \
  --fixture billing
```

You can also select by case id or coverage tag:

```sh
deno run -A jsr:@qlever-llc/trellis-test/integration/runner \
  --config trellis.integration.ts \
  --case billing.invoice-created
```

## 4. Run in parallel

Parallel mode starts one shared Trellis runtime host, writes a private manifest,
and runs selected case files with `deno test --parallel`. Worker tests attach to
the shared runtime when they use `runtimeScopeForCase(CASE_ID)`.

```sh
deno run -A jsr:@qlever-llc/trellis-test/integration/runner \
  --config trellis.integration.ts \
  --parallel \
  --fixture billing \
  --jobs 4
```

`--jobs <n>` does not become a `deno test --jobs` flag. The runner maps it to the
child process environment variable `DENO_JOBS=<n>`, which is how Deno controls
parallel test worker count. If you omit `--jobs`, Deno uses its default worker
count.

## Isolation contract

Parallel tests share one Trellis runtime, so isolation is the test author's
responsibility:

- keep one case per test module;
- use `runtimeScopeForCase(CASE_ID)` for behavior tests;
- scope contract ids with `caseScopedContractId(...)`;
- scope NATS subjects with `caseScopedSubject(...)`;
- scope service, client, resource, state, and business keys with
  `caseScopedName(...)` or an equivalent case slug;
- create the deployment and approve the contracts needed by the case;
- do not rely on cleanup from earlier tests or on execution order.

Case-scoped data is still useful for serial runs because it keeps reruns and
debugging predictable.

## Authority-plan notes

`runtime.contracts.approve(...)` is intentionally authority-aware. If a contract
change produces an unexpected authority plan, fix the contract or update the test
expectation instead of bypassing deployment authority.

Use `allowPlanClassifications: ["update"]` for ordinary mutable-dev additions.
Only include `"migration"` in tests that intentionally exercise migrations. For
tests that assert review behavior directly, inspect and act on plans through
`runtime.authority.plans.list(...)`, `runtime.authority.acceptUpdate(...)`,
`runtime.authority.acceptMigration(...)`, and
`runtime.authority.plans.reject(...)`.

## Troubleshooting

- **Docker, Podman, or NATS startup fails**: `@qlever-llc/trellis-test` starts an
  isolated NATS/JetStream container. Ensure `podman` or `docker` is on `PATH` and
  can run `docker.io/library/nats:2-alpine`. Startup failures before the Trellis
  URL is printed are usually container or port-publish issues.
- **Need to inspect generated runtime files**: set `TRELLIS_TEST_KEEP_WORKDIR=1`
  and have your config map that environment variable to `runtime.keepWorkdir`, as
  shown above. The workdir contains generated NATS config, Trellis config, logs,
  and the shared-runtime manifest in parallel runs.
- **Authority-plan failures**: check whether the failure is an ordinary update, a
  migration, or an incompatible contract change. Approve only the classifications
  the test is meant to cover, and prefer explicit authority-plan assertions when
  the plan itself is the behavior under test.
- **Flaky parallel cases**: look for unscoped contract ids, subjects, participant
  names, state keys, resource keys, or domain ids. Also confirm the module has
  only one `trellisIntegrationTest(...)` case and that the runner config's
  `testName` exactly matches the registered Deno test name.
